Leland refers to a park called in Welsh “Gorse nodiog”. It
has a fine woodland and a quarry of hardstone which is blackish “or sad marble
colour”, and there are slate stones. 

Ifor Williams comments on this that the name was probably
Garth-snodiog, referred to in the ‘Survey of the Honour of Denbigh’ in 1334.
Garth usually means a bluff, but can mean an enclosure or Park. Snodiog is
suggested to be a local dialect word meaning an area with many humps in the
land. The name was later corrupted to Park Snod-rook Park. He does not give the
location. (Ifor Williams (1941), Rhai Enwau Lleoedd yn Ninbych, Journal of the
Welsh Bibliographical Society, Vol. V, No. 5, p. 255).

An account of a storm in the area on 16 July 1706 refers to
Park-Snodiog, a rocky hill a short distance northward of Denbigh. (Philosophical
Transactions (1683-1775) Vol. 25 (1706 - 1707), p. 2343)

In 1726, land called Acr-y-forwyn in ‘Bannister Ucha’, a
township in Henllan parish was left to Denbigh Grammar school whose boundaries
were partly defined by reference to a boundary with Snodrook Park, also
referred to as ‘Crest’ (John Williams (1836) Ancient & Modern Denbigh: A
Descriptive History of the Castle, Borough … p. 296-7; House of Lords,
Enquiries Concerning Charities, Reports of Commissioners 1837-38  Vol 27, p.7).   In the 1841 Tithe map and apportionment for
this township, this would appear to correspond to numbers 8 and 9, which
together form a single strip, still held in trust for Denbigh School. This is
the site of a modern street Accar y Forwyn. 

National Library of Wales GB0210 File 298 date 1596/7 refers
to parcel of land “bounded on one side by the common called llewenie Greene and
on another by a lane running below a park called garth snodiog parke”. Lleweni
is east of the A525, but Lleweni Green might be the area now known as Denbigh
Green.

Clwyd Powys Archaeological Trust, Historical Environment
Record PRN 131108 refers to Snodiock (Garthsnodiock) Park at grid reference SJ04576671,
although the report they reference (Silvester & Hankinson, 2014) places it
to the west of the B5382. Silvester & Hankinson also refer to the enclosure
‘Snediock Park’ shown on Saxton and Speed maps, but not Leland. 

The area between the B5382 and the minor road running
northwards towards Green Ucha, south of Plas Heaton is a hill which today
includes wooded areas and a limestone quarry. The hilltop is called Crest Mawr.
This appears to be the area of Garth Snodiog, the former park. It could be
bounded with the Acr-y-Forwyn to the south, and the land in Denbigh Green (at
the minor road) to the east. The name Crest overlaps with the description given
in 1726, and it fits Leland’s description of it.

Flintshire record office have a survey of Snodiock Park  dated 1622/3 D/PT/803 – seen in catalogue,
not inspected.
